# Git — do not push to `main`

- **Never** run `git push` (or equivalent) targeting **`main`** as the remote branch. Do not `git push origin main`, do not force-push to `main`, and do not set upstream so that the default push goes to `main` for unmerged work.
- **Always** work on a **feature branch** (e.g. `feat/TICKET-description`, `fix/...`), push that branch to `origin`, and merge via **pull request** (or the repo’s required workflow).
- When suggesting or running git commands, prefer: `git checkout -b <branch>`, `git push -u origin <branch>`, then open or update a PR into `main`.
- If the user asks to “push to main” or deploy from `main` without a PR, **refuse the direct push** and offer: push the feature branch + merge via PR (or explain they must merge in GitHub/GitLab UI if they have permissions).

This matches typical protected-branch policies; treat `main` as read-only from local pushes unless the user explicitly confirms an emergency override **and** repository policy allows it.
